Integument papillated, with thin tunic with fine sediment particles forming a thin layer on body. Tubercles globose throughout body, of similar size, larger dorsally (
Fig. 22B
), smaller ventrally (
Fig. 22C
), arranged in about 6 transverse series per segment dorsally, and about 9 ventrally; posterior chaetigers with 4 transverse series per segment.

Branchiae cirriform, sessile on flat branchial plate, arranged in concentric rows, separated in two lateral groups, each with about 60 filaments (
Fig. 22E
). Branchiae about as long as palps. Nephridial lobes not seen.

Anterior dorsal margin of chaetiger 1 projecting forward, papillated. Chaetigers 1–3 of similar length. Chaetal transition from cephalic cage to body chaetae abrupt; aristate neurospines present from chaetiger 2. Gonopodial lobes dark brown, digitate, present in chaetiger 5 (
Fig. 22C
).

All notochaetae multiarticulate capillaries (most broken in 
holotype
), articles short basally and medially, subdistally medium-sized, long articles towards chaetal tips (
Fig. 22F
). Notochaetal bases of median chaetigers arranged in short transverse series, each with 3–4 chaetal bases (5 chaetae per bundle in better preserved specimens); about one-third as long as body width in better-preserved anterior fragments. Neurochaetae multiarticulate capillaries in chaetiger 1; aristate neurospines from chaetiger 2 (mostly broken), arranged in transverse series to end of body, 4–5 per bundle. Neurospines with very thin anchylose articles basally and medially, distally paler, almost hyaline, anchylose articles poorly defined, aristate (
Fig. 22G, H
).

Posterior end tapered, blunt (
Fig. 22D
); pygidium with anus terminal, anal cirri absent.
